The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring January 16, 2013, as Religious Freedom Day. The proclamation highlights the importance of religious freedom in America and the world. It mentions the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom, written by Thomas Jefferson and guided through the Virginia legislature by James Madison, as one of the first laws protecting religious freedom. The proclamation emphasizes that religious freedom is a universal human right that should be protected globally. It acknowledges the diversity of religious beliefs in America and encourages Americans to commemorate the day by promoting religious freedom and understanding.